# Salesforce schema read policy (ZERO TOLERANCE)

> **You MUST follow this rule before writing any code that touches a Salesforce object.** No exceptions. Skipping it leads to deployment failures, runtime errors, and silent data corruption. The schema files in `config/schema/` are the source of truth for AI agents; the org is the source of truth for the schema files. Both are kept in sync by `scripts/schemapy/auto_generate_schema.py`.
>
> If the schema files are missing or look stale, regenerate first: `python3 scripts/schemapy/auto_generate_schema.py`. Don't proceed against an empty `config/schema/`.

## The 7-file layout (per object)

Every object lives at `config/schema/objects/<ObjectApiName>/` with up to 7 small TOON files. Read them lazily — the strict sequence below tells you which file to open for which task.

```
config/schema/objects/<ObjectApiName>/
  schema.toon                  ALWAYS — slim index: object meta + counts + file pointers
  fields.toon                  ALWAYS — every field as one tabular row; lookups carry reference_path
  record_types.toon            optional — RecordTypes (api_name, label, description, active, record_count)
  validation_rules.toon        optional — validation rules + error formulas
  related_relationships.toon   optional — incoming references (parent -> child)
  picklists.toon               optional — TWO blocks: picklists: (single-select) + multipicklists: (multi-select)
  formulas.toon                optional — calculated field expressions
```

Plus three companion files at `config/schema/`:

```
_index.toon                    Master index of every object with file pointers
_search_index.toon             Lightweight cross-object field search
_junctions.toon                Detected junction objects + parent FKs + record counts
ER.md (project root)           Mermaid ER of every junction (read first for relationship overview)
```

## STRICT read sequence (the only sanctioned reading order)

There are TWO triggers — task-driven (what you're trying to do) AND field-driven (what you see on a row in fields.toon). Field-driven triggers fire on read AND write — they are the strictest.

### Field-driven mandatory reads (fire any time you SEE this on a fields.toon row)

| Field shape you see in fields.toon | What you MUST also open |
|---|---|
| `type: Picklist` | MUST open `objects/<X>/picklists.toon` and find the field name in the `picklists:` block. NEVER use any value not listed there. With `picklists_usage_status: live_counts`, prefer values where `count > 0`. |
| `type: MultiselectPicklist` | MUST open `objects/<X>/picklists.toon` and find the field name in the `multipicklists:` block. NEVER use any value not listed there. Per-value usage counts are NOT obtainable for multi-select. |
| `api_name: RecordTypeId` (Lookup, `reference_to: RecordType`) | MUST open `objects/<X>/record_types.toon` and use `api_name` (DeveloperName) to resolve the Id at runtime. NEVER hardcode the Id. With `usage_status: live_counts`, treat `record_count: 0` as deprecated. |
| `type: Lookup` or `MasterDetail` (any other) | MUST follow the `reference_path` cell to the parent's `schema.toon` and re-enter this table from the top. |

### Task-driven extras

| Task | Read in order |
|---|---|
| Any code that names a field, type, or constraint on Object X | `objects/<X>/schema.toon` (always) -> `objects/<X>/fields.toon` |
| Hit a validation error on deploy | + `objects/<X>/validation_rules.toon` |
| Traversing parent -> child (e.g. "what objects point AT X") | + `objects/<X>/related_relationships.toon` |
| Cross-object relationship overview ("how is everything wired up") | `config/schema/_junctions.toon` and `ER.md` |
| Field is calculated (formula behaves unexpectedly) | + `objects/<X>/formulas.toon` |

## Count semantics (the only sanctioned interpretation)

### picklists.toon — two blocks, two statuses, value+label always paired

Every `picklists.toon` carries TWO top-level blocks:

- `picklists:` — single-select picklist fields. These CAN be counted via SOQL `GROUP BY`. The block's status lives in `metadata.picklists_usage_status`.
- `multipicklists:` — multi-select picklist fields. These CANNOT be counted via SOQL `GROUP BY`. The block's status is ALWAYS `metadata.multipicklists_usage_status: not_applicable`.

Both blocks emit each picklist field as a tabular sub-block. Every row carries `label` and `value` columns. `value` is what you use in code, SOQL, and DML. `label` is what users see in the UI. They CAN differ (`value: PCP`, `label: Primary Care Physician`) — never assume they're the same.

Read `metadata.picklists_usage_status` FIRST when working with the `picklists:` block:

- `live_counts` — sub-blocks use `values[N]{label,value,count}:` form; `metadata.picklists_usage_collected_date` present.
  - `count: 0` means the value is DECLARED but ZERO records use it. Treat as deprecated unless seeding a brand-new picklist.
  - `count > 0` means the value is in active use; the number is the record total at collection time.
  - When `metadata.picklists_with_query_errors: [...]` is non-empty, those specific picklist fields couldn't be counted (SOQL failures); their sub-block falls back to `values[N]{label,value}:` (no count column).
- `not_collected` — sub-blocks use `values[N]{label,value}:` form (no count column). NEVER infer "deprecated" from absence of a count. `metadata.picklists_usage_not_collected_reason` (optional) explains why: `pending` (Step 10 hasn't run yet — default), `no_query_access` (the user can't query the object), `empty_object` (object has 0 records — every count would be 0), `query_error` (other SOQL failure).
- `not_applicable` — present only when there are no single-select picklists on this object (every picklist is multi-select).

For the `multipicklists:` block: sub-blocks always use `values[N]{label,value}:` form. The value list is the declared metadata, full stop. Per-value usage is unknowable through standard SOQL on multi-select picklists; do not seek count data.

### record_types.toon — every row already has api_name + label + count column

Shape: `record_types[N]{api_name,label,description,active,record_count}:`. `api_name` is the DeveloperName — the stable identifier you use in Apex (`Schema.SObjectType.<X>.getRecordTypeInfosByDeveloperName().get('<api_name>').getRecordTypeId()`). Treat `api_name` as the "value" half of the value+label pair.

`metadata.usage_status` is `live_counts` or `not_collected`:

- `live_counts` — `record_count` column present.
  - `record_count: 0` means the RecordType is DECLARED but ZERO records use it. Treat as deprecated unless your task is explicitly to seed a brand-new RecordType.
  - `record_count > 0` means the RecordType is in active use.
- `not_collected` — `record_count` column absent. NEVER infer "deprecated" from absence of a count. `metadata.usage_not_collected_reason` (optional) explains why with the same enum as picklists.

### Refreshing stale counts

```bash
python3 scripts/schemapy/auto_generate_schema.py            # full pipeline (~50 min)
python3 scripts/schemapy/collect_usage_stats.py --org {{ORG_ALIAS}}  # just Step 10 (~15-25 min)
python3 scripts/schemapy/collect_usage_stats.py --org {{ORG_ALIAS}} --objects Account,Case  # targeted
```

## fields.toon decoding rules (mandatory)

Every cell in `fields.toon` is a string on the wire so the file stays in TOON tabular form. Decode per the conventions documented in the file's own `metadata.cell_value_decoding`:

- `""` (empty string) — value is absent / null. Do NOT confuse with the literal string `""`.
- `"true"` / `"false"` — boolean.
- digit-only — integer.
- `"A|B|C"` (pipe-separated) — list of strings (currently used for polymorphic `reference_to` / `reference_path`).
- everything else — string.

`reference_path` is auto-computed from `reference_to`. For polymorphic refs it is pipe-aligned with `reference_to` slot-for-slot; an empty slot means the parent is not in this `config/schema/` snapshot (typically a system entity like `Group`).

## STRICT NEVER list

- NEVER write code that names a field without first opening `fields.toon` for that object.
- NEVER use a Picklist or MultiselectPicklist value (in code, SOQL, OmniScript, test data — anywhere) without first opening that object's `picklists.toon` and confirming the value is listed under the matching field name in the correct block (`picklists:` for single-select, `multipicklists:` for multi-select). Read or write, this rule applies.
- NEVER use a RecordType DeveloperName (or set RecordTypeId behavior on an object) without first opening that object's `record_types.toon` and finding the DeveloperName in the `api_name` column. Resolve the Id at runtime; never hardcode.
- NEVER assume `value` and `label` are the same for a picklist value — they commonly differ. Use the `value` column in code/SOQL/DML; the `label` column is for display.
- NEVER infer "deprecated" from absence of a count column. Check `picklists_usage_status` / `usage_status` first; only `live_counts` + `count: 0` (or `record_count: 0`) means deprecated.
- NEVER assume `relationship_name`. Read it from the FK row in `fields.toon`.
- NEVER navigate from a Lookup field to its parent without following `reference_path`. The parent might not be what the field name suggests (e.g. `PractitionerId` on a Health Cloud junction commonly references `Contact`, not anything called "Practitioner").
- NEVER edit any file under `config/schema/` by hand. Re-run `python3 scripts/schemapy/auto_generate_schema.py` instead.
- NEVER skim only the combined `config/salesforce-er-schema.toon` — it is the build intermediate, not the agent-facing source. Always read the per-object split.

## Refresh policy

`config/schema/` is regenerated by `scripts/schemapy/auto_generate_schema.py` (Steps 7–12). Re-run when:

- A field, picklist value, RecordType, or validation rule was just added/changed in the org.
- You suspect drift (e.g. a field referenced in a recent commit doesn't appear in `fields.toon`).
- `metadata.generated_date` on `config/schema/_index.toon` is more than a few days old and you're touching schema-sensitive code.

The full pipeline takes ~50 minutes for a 600+-object org. Steps 8 (split), 11 (junctions), 12 (ER) are fast and can be re-run independently. Step 10 (`collect_usage_stats.py`) can be re-run targeted at a single object via `--objects <Name>`.

## Worked example (generic — no org-specific assumptions)

Suppose you need to write Apex that creates a `Case` with a Contact reference, sets the `Type` picklist, and uses a specific RecordType.

1. Open `config/schema/objects/Case/schema.toon`. Confirm the object exists, see file pointers and counts.
2. Open `config/schema/objects/Case/fields.toon`. Find:
   - `ContactId` row — note `reference_to: Contact`, `reference_path: objects/Contact/schema.toon`.
   - `Type` row — note `type: Picklist`. (Field-driven trigger fires.)
   - `RecordTypeId` row — note `type: Lookup`, `reference_to: RecordType`. (Field-driven trigger fires.)
3. (Lookup follow-up.) Open `config/schema/objects/Contact/schema.toon` to confirm Contact exists and to traverse if you need any Contact field.
4. (Picklist trigger.) Open `config/schema/objects/Case/picklists.toon`. Locate the `Type` block under the top-level `picklists:` key. Read `metadata.picklists_usage_status`. With `live_counts`, choose only from values listed there with non-zero `count`; treat `count: 0` as deprecated.
5. (RecordTypeId trigger.) Open `config/schema/objects/Case/record_types.toon`. Find your intended RecordType by `api_name`. Use the `api_name` (DeveloperName) at runtime via `Schema.SObjectType.Case.getRecordTypeInfosByDeveloperName().get('<api_name>').getRecordTypeId()`. With `usage_status: live_counts`, treat `record_count: 0` as deprecated.
6. Now write the code.

## When the schema doesn't have what you need

If the org actually has a field/picklist/RecordType that isn't in `config/schema/`:

- Re-run `python3 scripts/schemapy/auto_generate_schema.py` first.
- If still absent, the org user/permission set you're using probably can't `describe` the object. That is a blocker — surface it explicitly. Don't guess the schema; don't open `sf sobject describe` results into your code path. Ask for the right credentials or scope.

